w Beginning in Germany tried to sustain grassroots movements without reproducing the bureaucratic, hierarchical, and supposedly obsolete structures of Social Democracy and Communism. Neoleftist militants experimented with alternative modes of organization such as councils, assemblies, and action committees. However, Renaud reveals that these same militants, decades later, often came to defend the very institutions they had opposed in their youth.Providing vital historical perspective on the challenges confronting leftists today, this book tells the story of generations of antifascists, left socialists, and anti-authoritarians who tried to build radical democratic alternatives to capitalism and kindle hope in reactionary times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLeft-wing extremistszEuropexHistory. 0aSocialismzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdvanced capitalism.  aAnti-fascism.  aAnti-imperialism.  aAntonio Gramsci.  aBolsheviks.  aBourgeoisie.  aCapitalism.  aCommunism.  aCommunist International.  aCommunist Party of Germany.  aComrade.  aCouncil communism.  aCounter-revolutionary.  aCritical theory.  aCriticism of capitalism.  aCritique of the Gotha Program.  aDemagogue.  aDenazification.  aDictatorship.  aDual power.  aEric Hobsbawm.  aFourth International.  aFrancoist Spain.  aFrankfurt School.  aFrench Left.  aGeorges Sorel.  aGerman re-armament.  aHeinrich Brandler.  aHeinrich Mann.  aHerbert Marcuse.  aHistory and Class Consciousness.  aHorst Mahler.  aIdeology.  aImperialism.  aJames Burnham.  aJohn Heartfield.  aKarl Liebknecht.  aKonrad Adenauer.  aKronstadt rebellion.  aKurt Hiller.  aKurt Schumacher.  aLeft communism.  aLeft-wing politics.  aLeninism.  aMarxism.  aMarxist hum